FILE REFERENCE — WHAT LIVES WHERE
================================================================================

  READ ONLY (from ETF system — never modify):
    etf_rankings.xlsx
    holdings_log.json

  AUTO-MAINTAINED (never edit manually):
    signals_log.json            all signals, ACTIVE or CLOSED
    trade_log.json              all closed trades with P&L
    iv_history.json             rolling IV history — builds up weekly

  MANUAL INPUTS (download from NSE each time):
    option-chain-ED-*.csv       one file per index per expiry

  OUTPUTS (regenerated each run):
    options_trades.xlsx         new signals (from options_trader.py)
    options_monitor.xlsx        MTM status (from options_monitor.py)
    trade_log.xlsx              P&L tracker (from options_tradelog.py)


================================================================================
QUICK REFERENCE — EXIT RULES
================================================================================

  Stop-loss   Exit when LTP falls to 50% of entry premium. No exceptions.
  Target      Exit when LTP reaches 2× entry premium (100% gain). Book it.
  Time stop   Exit 2 trading days before expiry. Regardless of P&L.

  All three exit levels are printed in options_trades.xlsx and shown in
  options_monitor.xlsx. You do not need to calculate anything manually.


================================================================================
COMMON ISSUES
================================================================================

  "No CSV files found"
    → Download option chain CSVs from nseindia.com/option-chain and place
      them in the same folder as the scripts. Do not rename the files.

  "No open ACTIVE positions found"
    → signals_log.json has no ACTIVE entries. Run options_trader.py first
      to generate signals, or check if all positions are already CLOSED.

  "IVR defaults to 40 (neutral)"
    → iv_history.json has fewer than 20 data points. This resolves after
      approximately 5 weekly runs. Signals are still valid — IVR just uses
      a neutral assumption until enough history is built up.

  "1 lot exceeds ₹25,000 budget"
    → The selected strike is too expensive for the budget. This typically
      happens on MIDCPNIFTY or with near-ATM strikes when premium is high.
      The script skips the signal automatically and logs the reason.

  Signal shows SKIPPED for an index you downloaded a CSV for
    → Check the filename. NSE sometimes changes the naming format slightly.
      The script detects: NIFTY, BANKNIFTY, FINNIFTY, MIDCPNIFTY, NIFTYNXT50.
      Ensure the index name appears in the filename as downloaded.

